Diseases of globalization
Globalization is being tested as severely as never before.
Everywhere, its tensions rumble.
The majority of Sub-Saharan Africa, South America, the Middle East, and Central Asia are stagnating or struggling with economic decline.
North America, Western Europe, and Japan are stuck in slow growth and risk another recession.
War now threatens in Iraq.
For supporters of open markets and free trade, this situation poses major challenges.
Why is globalization so threatened?
Why are its advantages apparently concentrated in only a few places?
Can a more balanced globalization be implemented?
There is no simple answer to these questions.
Open markets are necessary for economic growth, but they are barely sufficient.
Certain regions of the world have benefited greatly from globalization, particularly East Asia and China in recent years.
Some regions, however, have only gained meager benefits, particularly sub-Saharan Africa.
The American government claims that poor countries are responsible for the majority of the problems they face.
The slow growth of Africa, say American leaders, is caused by the incompetence of the African government.
However, life is more complicated than the Bush administration believes.
Let us consider the best-governed countries in Africa: Ghana, Tanzania, Malawi, and The Gambia.
Each of them has experienced a decline in living standards over the past two decades, while a large number of Asian countries that were among the last in international comparisons regarding the quality of government in each country (Pakistan, Bangladesh, Myanmar, and Sri Lanka) have experienced better economic growth.
It is true that economic performance is determined not only by governance standards, but also by geopolitics, geography, and economic structure.
Countries with large populations and therefore large internal markets tend to grow more rapidly than countries with small populations.
(As with all economic trends of this kind, there are counterexamples).
Coastal countries tend to be more successful than landlocked countries.
Countries with high levels of malaria tend to experience slower growth than countries with lower levels of malaria.
Developing countries neighboring rich markets, such as Mexico, tend to be more successful than those located far from the main markets.
These differences are of great importance.
If rich countries pay little attention to these structural issues, the gap between winners and losers will continue to widen.
If wealthy countries shift the responsibility onto unfortunate nations by claiming that they are in some way culturally or politically unsuitable to benefit from globalization, we will not only create deeper pockets of poverty but also intensify conflicts.
This, in turn, will lead to increased levels of violence, hostile reactions, and terrorism.
It is therefore time to move towards a more serious approach to globalization than the wealthy countries, and particularly the United States, offer.
This approach must begin with the most urgent task, namely meeting the basic needs of the world's poorest peoples.
In some cases, their suffering can be alleviated mainly through better governance within their country.
But in others, an honest look at the collected evidence will reveal that the main causes of poverty relate to diseases, climate instability, poor soils, market distances, etc.
An honest evaluation would indicate further that the poorest countries are unable to gather sufficient funds on their own to resolve such issues.
Rather than seeing rich countries give more lessons on the poor governance of poor countries, real solutions require that rich countries provide sufficient financial assistance to overcome the most deeply rooted barriers.
A case will strikingly illustrate this situation.
Disease control requires a health system capable of providing survival medications and basic preventive services such as bed nets to combat malaria and vitamins to fight nutritional deficiencies.
This system costs at least about $40 per person per year.
This amount represents only a grain of sand for rich countries that systematically spend more than $2,000 per person per year on health, but it exceeds the capacity of poor countries like Malawi, which have annual incomes of only $200 per person.
A healthcare system that works would cost more than the entire income of its government!
Even if Malawi is well-governed, its population will die in large numbers from diseases as long as it does not receive adequate assistance.
The success of globalization requires that we think more like doctors and less like preachers.
Rather than blaming the poor for their "sins," we must offer careful diagnoses, as any good doctor would, for each country and region, in order to understand the fundamental factors that delay their economic growth and development.
In some regions such as the Andes and Central Asia, the problem mainly stems from geographic isolation.
There, the task is to build roads, air links, and Internet connectivity to help these remote areas establish productive links with the world.
Rich countries must contribute to the financing of these projects.
In Sub-Saharan Africa, the main challenges concern disease control, soil fertility, and the development of educational opportunities.
Once again, a more significant foreign assistance is required.
In other regions, the main problems concern a lack of water, discrimination against women or other groups, or a variety of specific issues.
It is now time to take the complexities inherent to globalization seriously.
The ideology of a one-size-fits-all consensus from Washington is outdated.
On the eve of the war, it is urgent to tackle the difficult task of ensuring that everyone benefits from globalization.
We can achieve this if we remove the ideological blinders of the rich and if we mobilize a partnership between the rich and the poor.
Our common future depends on it.
